Introduction

Welcome to my ever-growing pile of crazy, stupid, and/or ridiculous stories I will probably never read. This is a showcase of my TBR (To Be Read) lista collection of books that I have impulsively plucked off the shelves of the internet and have thrown into this magnificent database. And while analyzing this database, we can together uncover the various trends and truths of my horrible taste.

What does my TBR say about me? Self-centered question, I know but this is the database Ive got.

Ill be using metrics like location, time period, tropes, genres and more to create graphs and answer questions which can show not only the trends over time when it comes to my preference, but the preferences of the publishing industry at large.

link to romance.io

Packages & Prep

This absolute monster of a database was created and curated by me, with the help of the greatest website ever made (and its wonderful user base), romance.io created by Silke.

Romance.io uses a one-of-a-kind tagging system that allows users to crowd source information on their favorite books. Users can go to any books page and tag whatever tropes they feel fits. You can even upvote and downvote any tags other users have left!

Of course, due to the nature of crowd sourcing information, not every book will be entirely accurate in its tags, and books that are less popular or are very old are much more likely to be missing tags or other information. We see this in the upcoming charts.

To showcase a final caveat

Clearly, when we compare the date a book was published versus the amount of tags it has, we see that theres definitely a correlation between recency and a higher amount of tags.

Now that weve established our data, lets dive into some stats

From this chart, we can see that theres not really one category to outweigh all. People arent just tagging the time period and being over it.

As with most things in life, women are slightly more underrepresented when it comes to available data

In Summary,

I indeed have bad taste.

But at least we got to see some interesting tidbits about what might be a quirk of mine, or is something to be considered about the population of readers out there, and even what might be a flaw of the publishing trends.
